  "designDecisions": [
    "WHAT: In-memory Map store in src/lib/store.ts as a module singleton with Maps for users, categories, transactions, and monthlyBudgetSummary. WHY: Zero setup — no Docker, no connection strings, no migrations. The store is imported once and lives for the process. UPGRADE PATH: Replace store.ts with a Prisma client module; all API route handlers already call typed store functions so only the store layer changes.",
    "WHAT: MonthlyBudgetSummary maintained as a Map<`${userId}:${categoryId}:${yearMonth}`, number> updated synchronously on every transaction create/update/delete. WHY: The PRD explicitly requires this pre-aggregated cache to hit ≤500ms budget summary response. Avoids iterating all transactions on every budget read. UPGRADE PATH: In a real DB this becomes a materialized view or a trigger-updated summary table.",
    "WHAT: Cookie-based sessions using a Map<token, userId> in src/lib/session.ts with crypto.randomUUID() tokens. WHY: The PRD specifies JWT but zero-dependency constraint prohibits jsonwebtoken or jose without npm install complexity adding external libs. UUID tokens stored in a server-side Map achieve equivalent auth isolation without any crypto. Comment in session.ts documents the JWT upgrade path. UPGRADE PATH: Replace token Map with jose (already a Next.js peer dep) to issue signed HS256 JWTs with 7-day expiry.",
    "WHAT: Passwords stored as plaintext in the in-memory Map store. WHY: The zero-external-dependency constraint means no bcrypt or argon2 (both require native bindings). This is an MVP-only demo; plaintext is clearly commented in store.ts and acceptable given all data is lost on restart anyway. UPGRADE PATH: npm install bcryptjs (pure JS, no native deps) and wrap password storage/comparison in src/lib/auth.ts hashPassword/verifyPassword functions.",
    "WHAT: Recharts for pie and bar charts installed via npm. WHY: The PRD requires hover/click interactivity (drill-down from pie to transactions) and re-render on month change — a canvas/SVG library is necessary. Recharts is React-native, TypeScript-typed, and requires only npm install recharts with no configuration. Alternative D3 would require significantly more code. UPGRADE PATH: None needed; Recharts scales well.",
    "WHAT: All monetary values stored as integer cents (amount_cents, limit_cents, spent_cents) throughout store, API, and UI. WHY: PRD mandates this explicitly to avoid float precision errors in aggregation. The UI divides by 100 only at display time. UPGRADE PATH: Same pattern in PostgreSQL (INTEGER or BIGINT columns).",
    "WHAT: Year-month bucketing uses string format 'YYYY-MM' computed from transaction date string. WHY: Transaction date is stored as a calendar date string (YYYY-MM-DD) per PRD — no timezone conversion needed at the store layer since users enter dates manually. The first 7 chars of the date give year-month directly. UPGRADE PATH: Add User.timezone awareness by resolving dates through date-fns-tz before bucketing.",
    "WHAT: Default categories seeded per-user at registration time (not globally shared). WHY: PRD requires categories to be user-scoped with user_id as a mandatory filter. Sharing global categories would require a different ownership model. Seeding per-user keeps the data model uniform. UPGRADE PATH: In a real DB, seed categories as a one-time INSERT triggered by user creation in a database transaction.",
    "WHAT: Separate src/lib/budgetUtils.ts for spending calculation and warning logic. WHY: The 90% budget warning must run both server-side (POST /api/transactions returns budget_warning in response) and be displayable client-side before final submit. Isolating this logic allows it to be imported from both API routes and potentially client components without duplication. UPGRADE PATH: No change needed.",
    "WHAT: Dashboard is a client component that fetches transactions and budget summary via fetch() calls, re-fetching after mutations without full page reload. WHY: PRD explicitly requires that saving a transaction triggers re-fetch of budget progress without full page reload. Using client-side state + fetch satisfies this without requiring a state management library. UPGRADE PATH: Replace with React Query or SWR for cache invalidation and optimistic updates."
